  "texts": [
    "These results suggest that while it may seem advisable for people involved in human-in-the-loop processes to explicitly report their judgments at the beginning, rather than merely supervising the AI and confirming or modifying the AI's assessments, AI errors are very likely to compromise their final decision even when those AI errors occur after accurate human judgment.",
    "Therefore, it is probably better that the human judgment occurs first, and then the AI, rather than the human, provides a second opinion, in order to detect (and warn) of potential human errors.",
    "But then again, we will still need a third party (an external human auditor, or a human committee) that should have the last word and be able to critically analyze any potential discrepancies in this human-AI collaboration.",
    "It is important to note that our experiments aimed to simulate the real-world systems, such as RisCanvi, in order to recreate the standard process of this type of automated systems.",
    "They were not experiments to evaluate RisCanvi."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}